Version Control Systems:
Source control systems help track changes in code, documents, and project files. They allow multiple people to work together without overwriting each other’s work.
There are two major types:
. Local Version Control Systems
	• Stores file versions only on your local computer.
	• Keeps track of changes using simple databases.
	• Example: RCS (Revision Control System).
	• Pros: Easy to use.
	• Cons: Not suitable for team collaboration.

🟦 1. Centralized Version Control Systems (CVCS)
	• Has one central server storing the main repository.
	• Developers check-out files, edit, then commit back to server.
	• Examples: SVN, Perforce, CVS.
✔️ Advantages
	• Easy to understand.
	• Centralized access control.
	• Simple backup and administration.
❌ Disadvantages
	• Single point of failure (if server is down, no one can work).
	• Requires constant internet connection.
	• Merging and branching can be difficult.

🟩 2. Distributed Version Control Systems (DVCS)
	• Every developer gets a full copy of the repository.
	• Work can be done offline.
	• Changes are later pushed/pulled to a shared server.
	• Examples: Git, Mercurial.
✔️ Advantages
	• Very fast (local commits).
	• Offline development possible.
	• Easy branching and merging.
	• More secure: multiple backups (every developer has a copy).
❌ Disadvantages
	• Initial learning curve.
	• Every developer stores the full repo → more disk usage.

 Cloud‑Based Source Control Platforms
(Not version control types, but tools built on top of Git)
	• Host repositories online for collaboration.
	• Examples: 
		○ GitHub
		○ GitLab
		○ Bitbucket
		○ Azure DevOps Repos
✔️ Advantages
	• Code hosting + access anywhere.
	• Integrates with CI/CD pipelines.
	• Pull requests, code reviews, issue tracking.
	• Excellent for team projects.


