1. What is a Repository (Repo)?
	• A repository is a container that holds your project files.
	• It also stores the entire history of changes.
	• Every Git project has a hidden folder .git → this stores the data.
👉 Think of a repo as a project + its time machine.

🟩 2. Working Directory (Working Tree)
	• This is the actual folder on your computer where your project files are kept.
	• You edit, create, delete files here.
	• Git can see these files, but they are not tracked until you tell Git to track them.
👉 Working directory = “Your work area”.

🟧 3. Staging Area (Index)
	• A temporary holding zone.
	• You use it to prepare which changes should go into the next commit.
	• You add files to this area using: 
git add <filename>
👉 Staging area = “Basket where you select items for checkout”.
You can:
	• Add files
	• Remove files
	• Change your mind
Nothing affects history until you commit.

🟥 4. Git Repository (Local Repo / Commit History)
	• Once you commit, the changes move from staging area into the local repository.
	• This becomes a permanent snapshot in the history.
Command:
git commit -m "message"
👉 Local repo = “History book of your project”.

🔷 5. Remote Repository (Optional but commonly used)
	• This is a copy of your repository stored on a server like: 
		○ GitHub
		○ GitLab
		○ Bitbucket
		○ Azure DevOps
	• Used for teamwork and backup.
Commands:
git push     → send your changes to remote
git pull     → get latest changes from remote

👉 Remote repo = “Online backup + collaboration point”.

🟨 6. Master Branch (or Main Branch)
	• Git starts with a default branch called master (older Git) or main (newer Git).
	• A branch is like a timeline of your code changes.
	• You can create your own branches to work separately.
👉 Branch = “Separate line of work”.


