Q1. Tell me about your project.
	"I built an end-to-end CI/CD pipeline on Azure Cloud for a React Expense Tracker application. The application tracks income and expenses. I used Azure DevOps for the pipeline, Docker for containerization, Azure Container Registry for storing images, and Azure Kubernetes Service for running the application. The entire process from code commit to live application is fully automated using GitFlow branching strategy. No manual steps are needed — when a developer pushes code everything happens automatically."

Q2. What is the main objective of your project?
	"The main objective was to implement a production-grade CI/CD pipeline following GitFlow branching strategy. The goal was to ensure that every code change goes through proper build, test, and deployment stages automatically. Feature branches only build and test. Develop branch deploys to DEV environment. Main branch deploys to production. No one can push directly to main without a PR review and passing build."

Q3. What technologies did you use and why?
		○ React JS — for the frontend application
		○ Docker — to containerize the app for consistent deployments
		○ Azure Container Registry — private registry to store Docker images securely
		○ Azure Kubernetes Service — managed Kubernetes platform to run containers
		○ Azure DevOps — for CI/CD pipeline, source code, and environments
		○ GitFlow — branching strategy to keep production always stable
		○ Self-hosted Linux VM — build agent for faster builds with cached tools
		○ Nginx — lightweight web server to serve the React static files

CATEGORY 2 — Azure Infrastructure Questions

Q4. What Azure resources did you create?
	"I created four main resources inside a Resource Group called devops-project in Central India:
		○ Azure Container Registry named ExpensetrackerappACR for storing Docker images
		○ AKS cluster named Expensetracker-AKS with Kubernetes 1.34.6 for running the app
		○ Linux VM named agentvm as self-hosted build agent
		○ All linked together — AKS is directly attached to ACR so it can pull images without extra credentials"

Q5. What is a Resource Group in Azure?
	"A Resource Group is a logical container in Azure that holds all related resources together. In my project I created one Resource Group called devops-project which contains the AKS cluster, ACR, and the build agent VM. It makes management easier — you can see all resources in one place, apply policies together, and delete everything at once when no longer needed."

Q6. What is Azure Container Registry and why did you use it?
	"Azure Container Registry is a private Docker registry hosted on Azure. I used it to store the Docker images built by the pipeline. It is private — only authorized users and services can push or pull images. The AKS cluster is directly linked to it using managed identity with AcrPull role so it can pull images without any username or password. Login server is expensetrackerappacr.azurecr.io."

Q7. What is AKS and why did you use it instead of running Docker directly?
	"AKS is Azure Kubernetes Service — a fully managed Kubernetes platform. I used it instead of running Docker directly because:
		○ Kubernetes automatically restarts pods if they crash
		○ It manages rolling updates without downtime
		○ It handles load balancing through Services
		○ It manages resource allocation across nodes
		○ Azure manages the control plane — I only manage the worker nodes Running Docker directly on a VM gives none of these benefits."

Q8. Why did you use a self-hosted agent instead of Microsoft-hosted agent?
	"I used a self-hosted agent for three reasons:
		○ Tools like Docker, Node.js, kubectl stay installed between runs — no reinstall needed — builds are faster
		○ Microsoft-hosted agents charge per minute — self-hosted has no extra cost
		○ Full control over the environment — I can install any specific version of tools needed
		○ The agent runs as a systemd service on the VM so it starts automatically on reboot without manual intervention"

CATEGORY 3 — GitFlow and Branching Questions

Q9. What is GitFlow? Why did you use it?
	"GitFlow is a branching strategy that defines how code flows from development to production. I used three branch levels:
		○ feature/* branches for development — build and test only
		○ Develop branch as integration branch — deploys to DEV environment
		○ main branch as production — deploys to live application I used GitFlow because it ensures broken code never reaches production. Every change must pass build validation and get reviewer approval before merging. This gives a clean, organized, and safe release process."

Q10. What are branch policies and why are they important?
	"Branch policies are rules enforced on branches that control how code can be merged. I configured:
		○ Minimum 1 reviewer must approve the PR before merge
		○ Build validation must pass — the pipeline must succeed
		○ No direct push allowed to main or Develop — only via Pull Request They are important because they prevent broken or unreviewed code from reaching important branches. Without policies anyone could push directly to main and break production."

Q11. What happens when a developer pushes code to a feature branch?
	"When code is pushed to a feature branch the pipeline triggers automatically. Only the Build stage runs:
		○ Install Node.js 16
		○ npm install to get dependencies
		○ npm run build to compile React app
		○ npm test to run tests If build and tests pass the developer raises a Pull Request to Develop. Docker push and deployment do not happen on feature branches — only build validation."

Q12. What happens when code is merged to Develop branch?
	"When a PR is merged to Develop the pipeline triggers and runs three things:
		○ Build and test the merged code
		○ Build Docker image and push to ACR with tag Develop-45 (branch name + build ID)
		○ Deploy to DEV environment using deployment.yaml and service-dev.yaml The app becomes available at http://4.247.195.11:8080 for testing."

Q13. What happens when code is merged to main branch?
	"When a PR is merged to main the pipeline triggers and:
		○ Builds and tests the merged code fresh
		○ Builds Docker image and pushes to ACR with tag main-22
		○ Deploys to production using deployment.yaml and service.yaml The production app is live at http://4.247.195.11 on port 80."

CATEGORY 4 — Docker Questions

Q14. What is Docker and why did you use it?
	"Docker is a containerization platform that packages an application with all its dependencies into a single unit called a container. I used Docker because:
		○ It ensures the app runs the same way everywhere — dev, DEV, and production
		○ The image is immutable — same image tested in DEV goes to production
		○ Containers are lightweight and start in seconds
		○ Kubernetes uses Docker images to create pods"

Q15. Explain your Dockerfile.
	"I used a two-stage Dockerfile: Stage 1 uses node:16-alpine as base. It copies package.json, runs npm install, copies source code, and runs npm run build. This compiles the React app into plain HTML, CSS and JavaScript files in the /app/build folder. Stage 2 uses nginx:alpine as base. It copies only the /app/build files from Stage 1. Node.js and all build tools are completely removed. The final image is only 25MB instead of 400MB because Node.js is not included in production."

Q16. What is a multi-stage Docker build? Why did you use it?
	"Multi-stage build means using multiple FROM statements in one Dockerfile. Each FROM starts a new stage. You can selectively copy files from one stage to another. I used it because:
		○ Build stage needs Node.js to compile React — but production does not need Node.js
		○ Without multi-stage the image would be 400MB including Node.js and node_modules
		○ With multi-stage I copy only the /app/build output to Nginx — final image is 25MB
		○ Smaller image means faster deployment, less storage cost, and smaller attack surface for security"

Q17. What is the difference between COPY and RUN in Dockerfile?
	"COPY copies files from local machine into the Docker image. For example COPY package.json ./ copies the package.json file into the container working directory. RUN executes a command inside the container during image build. For example RUN npm install runs npm install inside the container. Each RUN command creates a new layer in the image."

Q18. Why do you copy package.json before copying all source code?
	"This is a Docker caching optimization. Docker caches each layer. If I copy package.json first and run npm install, that layer is cached. When source code changes but package.json does not change, Docker reuses the cached npm install layer and skips reinstalling all packages. This saves 2 to 3 minutes on every build. If I copied all source code first, any code change would invalidate the npm install cache and reinstall everything every time."

Q19. What is the purpose of ENV CI=false in Dockerfile?
	"React's build process treats all warnings as errors when the CI environment variable is set to true. In a CI environment this is the default behavior. Without setting CI=false the build fails on any warning even minor ones. Setting ENV CI=false tells React to allow warnings during build without failing. This is needed for the Dockerfile to complete the npm run build step successfully."

Q20. Why did you use nginx:alpine in Stage 2?
	"I used nginx:alpine for two reasons:
		○ Nginx is a lightweight high-performance web server perfect for serving static files like HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. The React build output is just static files so Nginx is all we need.
		○ Alpine version is very small — only 5MB base image. Combined with the static files the final image is about 25MB which is very efficient. Node.js would be completely unnecessary at runtime since we are just serving files — not running JavaScript code."

CATEGORY 5 — Kubernetes Questions

Q21. What is Kubernetes and why did you use it?
	"Kubernetes is an open-source container orchestration platform. It automatically manages deploying, scaling, and running containers. I used it because:
		○ It automatically restarts containers if they crash
		○ It manages rolling updates — new version deploys without downtime
		○ Services provide stable network endpoints for pods
		○ Resource limits prevent one app from consuming all node resources
		○ AKS is fully managed — Azure handles the control plane"

Q22. What is a Pod in Kubernetes?
	"A Pod is the smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes. It is a wrapper around one or more containers. In my project each pod runs one container — the Nginx container serving the Expense Tracker app. The Deployment manages these pods — it ensures the correct number of pods are always running. If a pod crashes the Deployment automatically creates a new one."

Q23. What is the difference between a Deployment and a Pod?
	"A Pod is just a running container. If it crashes it stays dead. A Deployment is a controller that manages pods. It ensures the desired number of pods (replicas) are always running. If a pod crashes the Deployment automatically creates a new one to replace it. It also handles rolling updates — when you deploy a new image it creates new pods before removing old ones ensuring zero downtime."

Q24. Explain your deployment.yaml file.
	"My deployment.yaml has four key sections:
		○ Header: apiVersion apps/v1 and kind Deployment
		○ Metadata: name expensetracker and label app: expensetracker
		○ Spec: replicas 1, selector to find pods with matching label
		○ Container definition: image from ACR, imagePullPolicy Always, containerPort 80, resource requests of 100m CPU and 32Mi memory, limits of 200m CPU and 64Mi memory The pipeline overrides the :latest image tag with the actual build tag like Develop-45 at deploy time."

Q25. What is the difference between resource requests and limits?
	"Resource requests is the minimum CPU and memory a pod needs to be scheduled on a node. Kubernetes finds a node with enough free capacity based on this value. If no node has enough — pod stays in Pending state. Resource limits is the maximum CPU and memory the pod can use. If CPU exceeds the limit the container is throttled. If memory exceeds the limit the container is killed and restarted with OOMKill error. In my project I set requests to 100m CPU and 32Mi memory and limits to 200m CPU and 64Mi memory."

Q26. What is a Kubernetes Service? Why do you need it?
	"A Kubernetes Service is a stable network endpoint that exposes pods to the outside world. Pods are temporary — they get new IP addresses every time they restart. Without a Service there is no stable way to reach the pods. I used LoadBalancer type Service which creates an Azure public Load Balancer with a public IP. Internet traffic hits the public IP, the Service forwards it to the matching pods using label selectors."

Q27. What is the difference between service.yaml and service-dev.yaml?
	"Both are LoadBalancer Services but with two key differences: service.yaml for production uses port 80 and no fixed IP — Azure assigns the IP automatically. URL is http://4.247.195.11. service-dev.yaml for DEV uses port 8080 and has loadBalancerIP: 4.247.195.11 — a fixed existing IP. I used the same IP on different ports because my Azure for Students subscription has a limit of 3 public IPs and all 3 were already used. I could not create a 4th IP so I reused the existing one on port 8080 for DEV."

Q28. What is selector in Kubernetes Service?
	"Selector is a label-based matching mechanism that tells the Service which pods to send traffic to. In my service.yaml the selector is app: expensetracker. The Service finds all pods that have the label app: expensetracker and forwards traffic to them. This must match exactly with the labels defined in deployment.yaml template section. This is how Service and Deployment are connected."

Q29. What is imagePullPolicy: Always? Why did you use it?
	"imagePullPolicy: Always tells Kubernetes to always pull the latest image from ACR every time a pod starts — even if the image already exists on the node. I used this because my pipeline pushes a new image with the same latest tag on every deployment. Without Always policy Kubernetes might use the cached old image from the node and not pick up the new deployment. Always ensures the newest build is always running."

CATEGORY 6 — Pipeline Questions

Q30. Explain your CI/CD pipeline stages.
	"My pipeline has three stages: Stage 1 Build runs on all branches. It installs Node.js 16, runs npm install, builds the React app, runs tests, builds and pushes Docker image to ACR for main and Develop branches. Feature branches stop here. Stage 2 Deploy Dev runs only when Develop branch build succeeds. It applies deployment.yaml and service-dev.yaml to AKS deploying to DEV at port 8080. Stage 3 Deploy Prod runs only when main branch build succeeds. It applies deployment.yaml and service.yaml deploying to production at port 80."

Q31. What is a service connection in Azure DevOps?
	"A service connection is a stored credential in Azure DevOps that allows the pipeline to authenticate to external services without hardcoding passwords. I created two service connections: expenseSC — Docker Registry type pointing to ExpensetrackerappACR. The Docker task uses this to push images. kubernetesSC — Kubernetes type pointing to Expensetracker-AKS cluster. The KubernetesManifest task uses this to run kubectl apply."

Q32. What is a pipeline artifact? Why did you use it?
	"A pipeline artifact is a file or folder published by one stage and downloaded by another stage in the same pipeline run. I published the k8s folder containing deployment.yaml, service.yaml, and service-dev.yaml as an artifact in the Build stage. The Deploy stages download this artifact to get the manifest files. This is needed because different stages run independently and cannot directly access each other's files."

Q33. What is the KubernetesManifest task?
	"KubernetesManifest is a built-in Azure DevOps task that applies Kubernetes manifest files to a cluster. Internally it runs kubectl apply. The important inputs are:
		○ action: deploy — runs kubectl apply
		○ kubernetesServiceConnection — authenticates to AKS
		○ namespace — which namespace to deploy to
		○ manifests — the yaml files to apply
		○ containers — this injects the exact image tag at deploy time overriding the image in deployment.yaml"

Q34. Why do you use (Build.SourceBranch�ame)−(Build.BuildId) as image tag?
	"I use this combination for two reasons: Build.SourceBranchName gives the branch name — Develop or main. This makes it clear which branch the image came from. Build.BuildId is a unique auto-incremented number for each pipeline run. This makes every build uniquely identifiable. So Develop-45 means it was built from Develop branch in pipeline run 45. If there is a problem in production I can identify exactly which build caused it and roll back to a previous tag like Develop-44."

Q35. What is dependsOn in pipeline stages?
	"dependsOn specifies that a stage can only start after another stage completes. In my pipeline Deploy_Dev and Deploy_Prod both have dependsOn: Build. This means deployment only starts if the Build stage completed. If build fails deployment never runs — broken code never reaches any environment. This is a critical safety mechanism in the pipeline."

Q36. What is an Environment in Azure DevOps?
	"An Environment in Azure DevOps is a logical representation of a deployment target like development or production. I created two environments — development and production. Every deployment is recorded in the environment with timestamp, build number, and success or failure status. This gives a complete audit trail of what was deployed when and by which pipeline run. You can also add approval gates on environments — for example requiring manual approval before deploying to production."

CATEGORY 7 — Challenges Questions

Q37. What challenges did you face in this project?
	"I faced 13 real challenges. The most significant ones were:
		1. Node.js and webpack version incompatibility — webpack 4 does not support Node 18 OpenSSL 3.0. Fixed by downgrading to Node 16.
		2. Azure public IP quota limit — Azure for Students only allows 3 IPs and all were used. Fixed by sharing the same IP for DEV and PROD on different ports.
		3. Pods in Pending state — CPU requests were too high for the small AKS node. Fixed by reducing CPU requests from 250m to 100m and replicas from 2 to 1.
		4. Docker permission denied — agent user not in docker group. Fixed by usermod and chmod on the VM."

Q38. How did you resolve the Public IP limit issue?
	"My Azure for Students subscription allows only 3 public IPs in Central India. All 3 were used — one for the agent VM, one for AKS internal load balancer, and one for the production service. When I tried to create a LoadBalancer service for DEV environment Azure could not provision a 4th IP and threw PublicIPCountLimitReached error. I resolved it by using the same existing IP 4.247.195.11 for both environments but on different ports. Production uses port 80 without a fixed IP specification. DEV uses port 8080 with loadBalancerIP: 4.247.195.11 to reuse the existing IP. This way both environments share one IP without needing a second one."

Q39. How did you fix the pods Pending issue?
	"I ran kubectl describe pod and found the event message: 0/1 nodes available Insufficient cpu. Then I ran kubectl describe nodes and saw the node was at 89% CPU usage with only 198m CPU free. My deployment.yaml had replicas: 2 with cpu requests: 250m each — total 500m which exceeded available CPU. I fixed it by reducing replicas to 1 and cpu requests from 250m to 100m and memory from 64Mi to 32Mi. After this the pod was successfully scheduled and entered Running state."

Q40. Why did you face the InvalidImageName error?
	"My Azure Repos branch was named Develop with a capital D. The pipeline variable Build.SourceBranchName returns the exact branch name — so it returned Develop with capital D. The Docker image was pushed with tag Develop-39. But in the pipeline conditions and trigger I had written develop with lowercase d in some places. This caused a mismatch — the condition for Deploy stage was checking refs/heads/develop lowercase and never matched refs/heads/Develop uppercase so the deployment tried to pull develop-39 lowercase which did not exist in ACR. I fixed it by making all references consistently use capital Develop throughout the trigger, conditions, and image tag."

CATEGORY 8 — General DevOps Questions

Q41. What is CI/CD?
	"CI stands for Continuous Integration — automatically building and testing code every time a developer pushes changes. CD stands for Continuous Deployment — automatically deploying the tested code to environments. In my project CI happens in the Build stage — every push triggers build and test. CD happens in Deploy stages — after build passes the app is automatically deployed to DEV or PROD based on the branch."

Q42. What is the difference between CI and CD?
	"CI — Continuous Integration — focuses on automatically building and testing code whenever developers push changes. The goal is to detect integration problems early. CD — Continuous Deployment — focuses on automatically deploying the tested and validated code to target environments. In my project Develop branch triggers CD to DEV and main branch triggers CD to PROD. Together they ensure code is always tested before deployment and deployment is always automated."

Q43. What is a namespace in Kubernetes?
	"A namespace is a way to logically divide a single Kubernetes cluster into multiple virtual clusters. In my project I used the default namespace for both DEV and PROD deployments since I had only one AKS cluster. In a production setup you would typically have separate namespaces like develop, staging, and production within the same cluster to keep workloads isolated from each other."

Q44. What is kubectl?
	"kubectl is the command line tool for interacting with a Kubernetes cluster. Common commands I used:
		○ kubectl get pods — check if pods are running
		○ kubectl get services — check external IP and ports
		○ kubectl describe pod — see detailed info and events
		○ kubectl get nodes — check node status
		○ kubectl apply -f file.yaml — apply manifest files
		○ kubectl get deployment — check deployment status"

Q45. What is the difference between Docker image and Docker container?
	"A Docker image is a read-only template — like a blueprint or a class in programming. It contains the application code, dependencies, and configuration baked in. A Docker container is a running instance of an image — like an object created from a class. You can run multiple containers from the same image. In my project the pipeline builds and pushes the image to ACR. Kubernetes creates containers from that image when it starts pods."

CATEGORY 9 — Scenario Based Questions

Q46. What happens if the build fails on a feature branch?
	"If the build fails on a feature branch the pipeline shows a failed status in Azure DevOps. The branch policy on Develop is set to require a passing build before PR can be completed. So the developer cannot merge the failing feature branch into Develop until the build is fixed. This ensures only working code enters the Develop integration branch."

Q47. What happens if deployment to DEV fails?
	"If deployment to DEV fails the pipeline shows a failed status in the Deploy_Dev stage. The DEV environment dashboard in Azure DevOps records the failed deployment with a red status. The production environment is completely unaffected — main branch has its own separate Deploy_Prod stage which only triggers on main branch. DEV and PROD deployments are independent of each other."

Q48. How do you verify the deployment was successful?
	"After deployment I verify using these kubectl commands:
		○ kubectl get pods — check pods are in Running state with 1/1 Ready
		○ kubectl get services — check EXTERNAL-IP is assigned and ports are correct
		○ kubectl get deployment — check desired and available replicas match Then I open the browser — http://4.247.195.11:8080 for DEV and http://4.247.195.11 for PROD and confirm the Expense Tracker app loads correctly."

Q49. How do you roll back a bad deployment?
	"Since I tag every Docker image with branch name and build ID like Develop-45, I can roll back by:
		○ Updating the image tag in deployment.yaml to a previous working version like Develop-44
		○ Running kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
		○ Or in the pipeline re-running a previous successful pipeline run which redeploys the previous image Kubernetes performs a rolling update during rollback ensuring zero downtime."

Q50. If you had more time what would you improve in this project?
	"I would add several improvements:
		○ Add manual approval gate on production environment so someone must approve before every PROD deploy
		○ Set up Azure Monitor and Container Insights for proper pod monitoring and alerting
		○ Add Horizontal Pod Autoscaler to automatically scale pods based on CPU usage
		○ Use Azure Key Vault to store secrets instead of hardcoding in manifests
		○ Add a staging environment between DEV and PROD for UAT testing
		○ Implement blue-green or canary deployment strategy for zero-risk production releases
		○ Request quota increase to get more public IPs so DEV and PROD have separate IPs"

