Q1. What is Azure DevOps? A Microsoft platform offering end-to-end DevOps tools — Boards, Repos, Pipelines, Test Plans, and Artifacts — to plan, build, test, and deploy software.
Q2. What is Azure Pipelines? A CI/CD service that automates building, testing, and deploying code to any platform or cloud using YAML or classic GUI-based pipelines.
Q3. What is the difference between CI and CD? CI (Continuous Integration) automatically builds and tests code on every commit; CD (Continuous Delivery/Deployment) automatically deploys validated code to target environments.
Q4. What is a YAML pipeline? A pipeline defined as code in an azure-pipelines.yml file stored in the repo — version-controlled, reviewable via PRs, and reusable across projects.
Q5. What are stages, jobs, and steps? Stage is a logical phase (Build/Deploy); Job is a set of steps running on one agent; Step is a single task or script — hierarchy is Pipeline → Stage → Job → Step.
Q6. What is an agent pool? A collection of agents (machines) that run pipeline jobs — Microsoft-hosted pools are managed by Azure; self-hosted pools are machines you configure and maintain.
Q7. What is a service connection? A stored credential/endpoint in Azure DevOps that allows pipelines to securely connect to external services like Azure subscriptions, Docker Hub, or Kubernetes.
Q8. What is a variable group? A shared set of variables (including secrets) that can be linked across multiple pipelines — can be backed by Azure Key Vault for secure secret management.
Q9. What are pipeline templates? Reusable YAML fragments (stages/jobs/steps) stored in a central repo and referenced across pipelines to enforce DRY principles and governance.
Q10. What is an Environment in Azure Pipelines? A logical target for deployments (e.g., Dev, QA, Prod) that tracks deployment history, supports approval gates, and records which version was deployed where.
Q11. What are approval gates? Checks configured on an Environment that pause a pipeline and wait for designated approvers before allowing deployment to proceed.
Q12. What are deployment strategies? Patterns for releasing updates — runOnce (deploy once), rolling (replace instances gradually), canary (shift small traffic % first then full rollout).
Q13. What is Azure Repos? A source control service supporting Git (distributed) and TFVC (centralized) repositories with branch policies, PRs, and code review workflows.
Q14. What are branch policies? Rules enforced on protected branches (like main) — requiring reviewers, a passing build, linked work items, or specific merge strategies before a PR can merge.
Q15. What is Azure Boards? An Agile project management tool supporting work items, backlogs, sprint planning, Kanban boards, and burndown charts across Scrum/Agile/CMMI processes.
Q16. What is the difference between a Kanban board and a Sprint board? Kanban shows continuous flow of all backlog items across columns; Sprint board shows only items committed to the current sprint broken down into tasks.
Q17. What is Azure Artifacts? A package management service supporting NuGet, npm, Maven, PyPI, and Universal Packages — with upstream source proxying and caching from public registries.
Q18. What is RBAC in Azure DevOps? Role-Based Access Control assigns permissions at org, project, or object level — roles like Project Administrator, Contributor, and Reader control what users can do.
Q19. What are pipeline decorators? Extension-based steps injected automatically into every pipeline across an org (e.g., security scans) — invisible to pipeline authors, used for governance enforcement.
Q20. What is workload identity federation? A secretless authentication method for Azure service connections using OIDC tokens — eliminates the need to store or rotate credentials in Azure DevOps.
Q21. What is a fork vs a branch? A branch is a pointer within the same repo; a fork is a full copy of the repo under a different account — used when contributors lack direct write access.
Q22. What is a trigger in Azure Pipelines? A condition that starts a pipeline automatically — CI triggers fire on code push, PR triggers on pull requests, scheduled triggers on a cron schedule.
Q23. What is a multi-stage pipeline? A single YAML pipeline with separate stages for each environment (Dev → QA → Prod), using dependsOn for sequencing and approvals for controlled promotion.
Q24. What is condition in a pipeline? A YAML expression that controls whether a step/job/stage runs — e.g., condition: eq(variables['Build.SourceBranch'], 'refs/heads/main') to deploy only from main.
Q25. What is artifact publishing and downloading? PublishBuildArtifacts uploads build outputs (binaries, packages) from one stage; DownloadBuildArtifacts retrieves them in a later stage for deployment.

Kubernetes
Q: What is Kubernetes? A: Open-source container orchestration platform that automates deployment, scaling, and management of containerized apps. Google open-sourced it in 2014.
Q: What is a Pod? A: Smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes holding one or more containers sharing the same network and storage. All containers in a pod run on the same node.
Q: What is a Node? A: A physical or virtual machine that runs pods managed by the control plane. Each node has kubelet, kube-proxy, and a container runtime.
Q: What is a Deployment? A: Controller that manages stateless pods ensuring desired replicas are always running. Supports rolling updates and rollbacks.
Q: What is a ReplicaSet? A: Ensures a specified number of pod replicas are running at all times. Deployments manage ReplicaSets automatically — rarely used directly.
Q: What is a Service? A: Stable network endpoint that exposes pods using label selectors. Types: ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer, ExternalName.
Q: ClusterIP vs NodePort vs LoadBalancer? A: ClusterIP is internal only; NodePort exposes on a static port on each node; LoadBalancer provisions a cloud LB with an external IP.
Q: What is a Namespace? A: Virtual cluster within Kubernetes to isolate resources between teams or environments. Default namespaces: default, kube-system, kube-public.
Q: What is a ConfigMap? A: Stores non-sensitive config data as key-value pairs injected into pods as env vars or volume files. Decouples config from container images.
Q: What is a Secret? A: Stores sensitive data like passwords in base64-encoded form. Not encrypted by default — use Vault or KMS for real encryption.
Q: What is a StatefulSet? A: Manages stateful apps needing stable network IDs and persistent storage (e.g., databases). Pods are created/deleted in order unlike Deployments.
Q: What is a DaemonSet? A: Ensures one pod runs on every node. Commonly used for log collectors, monitoring agents, and network plugins.
Q: What is a PersistentVolume (PV)? A: Cluster-level storage resource provisioned by an admin or dynamically via StorageClass. Decouples storage from the pod lifecycle.
Q: What is a PVC? A: PersistentVolumeClaim is a user request for storage that binds to a matching PV. Pods use PVCs to mount persistent storage.
Q: What is kube-scheduler? A: Watches for unscheduled pods and assigns them to the best node based on resource requests, affinity rules, and taints/tolerations.
Q: What is etcd? A: Distributed key-value store that holds all Kubernetes cluster state and configuration. It is the single source of truth for the control plane.
Q: What is kubelet? A: Agent on every node that ensures containers in PodSpecs are running and healthy. Talks to the API server and manages pod lifecycle.
Q: What is kube-proxy? A: Network proxy on each node that maintains iptables/IPVS rules to route traffic to the correct pod for each Service.
Q: What are Liveness and Readiness probes? A: Liveness restarts a container if it becomes unhealthy; Readiness removes a pod from Service endpoints until it is ready to serve traffic.
Q: What are Resource Requests and Limits? A: Requests are minimum CPU/memory needed for scheduling; Limits are the maximum before throttling or OOM-kill.
Q: What is HPA? A: Horizontal Pod Autoscaler scales pod replicas based on CPU, memory, or custom metrics. Works with Deployments and StatefulSets.
Q: What is VPA? A: Vertical Pod Autoscaler adjusts CPU/memory requests for pods based on actual usage. Requires a pod restart to apply changes.
Q: What are Taints and Tolerations? A: Taints repel pods from nodes; Tolerations on pods allow them to be scheduled on tainted nodes. Used to dedicate nodes for specific workloads.
Q: What is Node Affinity? A: Rules that constrain which nodes a pod can be scheduled on based on node labels. Required affinity is hard; preferred affinity is soft.
Q: What is a Job and CronJob? A: A Job runs pods to completion (batch tasks); a CronJob schedules Jobs on a cron time expression.
Q: What is an Ingress? A: API object that manages HTTP/HTTPS routing to services via host/path rules. Requires an Ingress Controller (e.g., NGINX, Traefik) to function.
Q: What is RBAC? A: Role-Based Access Control restricts who can do what in the cluster. Key objects: Role, ClusterRole, RoleBinding, ClusterRoleBinding.
Q: What is a ServiceAccount? A: An identity for pods to authenticate with the Kubernetes API. Pods use the ServiceAccount token to call API server endpoints.

AKS
Q: What is AKS? A: Azure Kubernetes Service is Microsoft's fully managed Kubernetes offering. Azure handles the control plane — you only manage and pay for worker nodes.
Q: How does AKS differ from self-managed Kubernetes? A: AKS fully manages the control plane (upgrades, patching, HA) at no cost. You only provision and pay for agent node pools.
Q: What is an AKS Node Pool? A: A group of VMs with the same configuration (size, OS, Kubernetes version). AKS supports multiple node pools per cluster for mixed workloads.
Q: What is the AKS system node pool? A: Required node pool that runs critical system pods like CoreDNS and metrics-server. Must use Linux nodes with at least 2 vCPUs.
Q: What is Azure CNI vs Kubenet in AKS? A: Azure CNI assigns real VNET IPs to every pod (more IPs needed); Kubenet uses NAT with fewer IPs but limited network policy support.
Q: What is AKS Cluster Autoscaler? A: Automatically adds or removes nodes in a node pool based on pending pod demand and node utilization. Configured per node pool with min/max counts.
Q: What is Azure AD integration in AKS? A: Allows Azure AD users and groups to authenticate to AKS via RBAC bindings. Uses managed identity — no manual credential management needed.
Q: What is AKS Workload Identity? A: Lets pods use Azure AD federated credentials to access Azure resources without storing secrets. Replaces the older pod identity approach.
Q: What is Azure Key Vault Secrets Provider for AKS? A: A CSI driver addon that mounts Azure Key Vault secrets as volumes into pods. Secrets sync automatically when updated in Key Vault.
Q: What is AKS Managed Identity? A: Azure-managed identity assigned to the AKS cluster to interact with Azure resources (ACR, VNET, disks) without storing credentials in code.
Q: How do you upgrade an AKS cluster? A: Run az aks upgrade — control plane upgrades first, then node pools are cordoned/drained/reimaged one by one to minimize downtime.
Q: What is ACR integration with AKS? A: Attaches an Azure Container Registry to AKS using --attach-acr so the cluster can pull images without separate pull secrets.
Q: What is Azure Monitor for AKS? A: Container Insights collects metrics and logs from pods/nodes into Log Analytics. Enables dashboards and alerts in Azure Monitor.
Q: What are AKS Virtual Nodes? A: Allow AKS to burst pods to Azure Container Instances instantly without provisioning new VMs. Uses Virtual Kubelet under the hood.
Q: What is an AKS Spot Node Pool? A: Uses low-cost Azure Spot VMs for fault-tolerant batch workloads. Spot nodes can be evicted with 30 seconds notice.
Q: What is the AKS API server authorized IP range? A: Restricts which IPs can reach the Kubernetes API server public endpoint. Improves security by limiting exposure to known IPs.
Q: What is a Private AKS Cluster? A: API server has no public endpoint — only reachable via Private Link within the VNET. Requires Azure Private DNS for name resolution.
Q: What is GitOps with AKS (Flux)? A: The AKS GitOps addon uses Flux v2 to continuously sync cluster state from a Git repo. Changes to Git automatically apply to the cluster.

Advanced
Q: What is a Network Policy? A: Kubernetes resource that controls pod-to-pod traffic using label selectors. Requires a CNI plugin that supports it (Calico, Azure NPM, Cilium).
Q: What is a PodDisruptionBudget (PDB)? A: Limits how many pods can be unavailable during voluntary disruptions like upgrades or node drains. Ensures minimum availability.
Q: What is an Init Container? A: Runs to completion before app containers start in a pod. Used for setup tasks like loading configs or waiting for services.
Q: What is a Sidecar Container? A: Helper container in the same pod that adds functionality like logging or auth (e.g., Envoy in a service mesh).
Q: What is a CRD? A: Custom Resource Definition extends the Kubernetes API with new resource types. Combined with a custom controller, it manages complex apps declaratively.
Q: What is the Operator pattern? A: A Kubernetes controller that encodes operational knowledge for a stateful app using CRDs and control loops (e.g., backups, upgrades).
Q: What is Helm? A: Package manager for Kubernetes that bundles manifests into charts with templating and versioning. helm install/upgrade deploys apps easily.
Q: What is a Service Mesh (e.g., Istio)? A: Dedicated infrastructure layer for service-to-service communication providing mTLS, traffic management, observability, and circuit breaking.
Q: What is OPA/Gatekeeper? A: Open Policy Agent with Gatekeeper enforces custom admission policies (e.g., require resource limits) using Rego rules as ValidatingWebhookConfigurations.
Q: What is KEDA? A: Kubernetes Event-Driven Autoscaler scales deployments to zero or based on external event sources (queues, Kafka, HTTP). Works alongside HPA.
Q: What is pod topology spread? A: Uses topologySpreadConstraints to evenly distribute pods across zones or nodes, improving HA and avoiding single-AZ concentration.
Q: Why is etcd backup critical? A: etcd holds all cluster state — losing it means losing the cluster. Back up regularly using etcdctl snapshot save and store off-cluster.
Q: What is a Validating vs Mutating Webhook? A: Mutating webhooks modify resource fields on admission (e.g., inject sidecars); Validating webhooks approve or reject resources based on policy.



Taint
	"A taint is a restriction placed on a node that prevents pods from being scheduled on it unless the pod has a matching toleration."

Toleration
	"A toleration is added to a pod to allow it to be scheduled on a node that has a matching taint."

Node Affinity
	"Node affinity is a rule on a pod that says which nodes it prefers or must run on, based on node labels."

Pod Affinity
	"Pod affinity is a rule that schedules a pod close to another pod — like running a web app on the same node as its Redis cache for low latency."

Pod Anti-Affinity
	"Pod anti-affinity is a rule that schedules a pod away from another pod — like spreading replicas across different nodes for high availability."

One Liner Difference
Taint          →  Node repels pods
Toleration     →  Pod handles node restriction
Node Affinity  →  Pod attracted to a node
Pod Affinity   →  Pod attracted to another pod
Anti-Affinity  →  Pod repelled from another pod

Bonus — Interviewer Follow-up Answers
Q: Difference between Taint and Node Affinity?
	"Taint is set on the node to repel pods. Node Affinity is set on the pod to attract it to a node."
Q: Can a pod with toleration still run on normal nodes?
	"Yes — toleration only means the pod can run on tainted node, not that it must. Use Node Affinity to force it."
Q: When would you use Pod Anti-Affinity?
	"To spread replicas across nodes so if one node fails, other replicas are still running — ensuring high availability."











